<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>you don’t say so • you may well say so</xh5><p> <i>you don’t say so—</i>is used to express surprise or sarcasm at what smb. has just said: I explained my presence, and he said: “<u>You don’t say so</u>! Why, I’ve got a patient over at Swampscott, who says he knows you.</p><p> <i>you may well say so—</i>what you say is perfectly correct, justified, etc.: “A craft that’s good for sore eyes.” “<u>You may well say so</u>,” replied the commodore. “There is no finer schooner-yacht afloat.”</p> </entry>
